posts.name: Benjamin Hall
posts.cooked:
Some things I notice:

In Phoenix 6, Talon FX uses canonical units of rotations, not ticks. So you don’t need TICKS_PER_REVOLUTION , just pass in rotations ( degrees / 360.0 ).

As mentioned with the compiler warning, setInverted() is going to be removed next season, so it should be replaced with configuring invert using a TalonFXConfiguration ( example ).

You also need to set up PID gains for position control using configs.

If you’re not familiar with Phoenix 6, I would read over our documentation on general API usage . From there, you can look at our Closed-Loop Overview and Basic PID and Profiling documentation.

posts.name: Benjamin Hall
posts.cooked:
You still have TICKS_PER_REVOLUTION , which you don’t want with Phoenix 6. I would alsonapply your PID configs in the constructor along with invert; configs are blocking operations and should not be applied periodically. Besides that, it should mostly be just tuning PID gains.

You can also look at our PositionClosedLoop example for reference.

posts.name: Benjamin Hall
posts.cooked:
Yes. You probably don’t need both PositionVoltage and PositionTorqueCurrentFOC , just pick whichever you want to use (note that TorqueCurrentFOC requires Phoenix Pro). That would also mean you only need to set up and tune PID gains on Slot0. You also probably don’t need the peak forward/reverse voltage/torquecurrent configs, and you can strip out the println s (otherwise you may flood the Driver Station).

Once you confirm everything is working, you can also look into profiling the motion using Motion Magic® to improve overall system behavior, particularly for arms and elevators. It’s basically an extra 3 configs and using MotionMagicVoltage instead of PositionVoltage .
